<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>CALIPER DISC BRAKES - SERVICE INFORMATION - CALIPER BRAKE NOISE (RATTLE)</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="describe" graphiccount="3">
        <title>CALIPER BRAKE NOISE (RATTLE)</title>
        <para>Some vehicles equipped with disc hydraulic brakes may experience a brake noise (rattle). This condition is
            due to wear of the caliper and the anchor plate sliding surfaces. To correct this condition, follow the
            procedures described below.
        </para>
        <para>If wear measured at the bumper gap (
            <hotlnk xrefid="f0401611">Figure 11</hotlnk>) is not beyond the maximum allowable wear listed in ,
            <hotlnk xrefid="hl0401604">Table 1
                <xref refid="hl0401604"/>
            </hotlnk>
            , a shim may be added between the caliper and anchor plate. If the wear exceeds the maximum allowed wear
            listed in ,
            <hotlnk xrefid="hl0401604">Table 1
                <xref refid="hl0401604"/>
            </hotlnk>
            , the caliper and/or anchor plate needs to be replaced.
        </para>
        <figure id="f0401611" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g0401611" filename="../figg04/G0401611.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
            <caption>Figure 11. Disc Brake Components with Shim Kit</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1>1. CALIPER ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                <callout1>2. V-WAY SURFACE</callout1>
                <callout1>3. SHIM</callout1>
                <callout1>4. SUPPORT SPRING</callout1>
                <callout1>5. RETAINING BOLT</callout1>
                <callout1>6. SUPPORT KEY</callout1>
                <callout1>7. ANCHOR PLATE</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <para>The following procedure should be followed to select the proper shim to reduce the bumper gap if
            necessary.
        </para>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the support key retaining bolt and tap the support key and spring out of the V-way
                between the caliper and anchor plate (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0401612">Figure 12</hotlnk>). Remove the caliper from the anchor plate.
            </para>
            <figure id="f0401612" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0401612" filename="../figg04/G0401612.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 12. Measuring Caliper Wear</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. STRAIGHT EDGE</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. FEELER GAUGE</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Clean the V-way surface of the caliper and anchor plate with a wire brush. Use a file to
                remove any nicks, burrs or gouges.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Lay a straight edge across the caliper V-way surface as shown (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0401612">Figure 12</hotlnk>) and measure the wear on these surfaces with a feeler
                gauge.
                <emph type="bold">Calipers that display wear of .050 inch or greater must be replaced.</emph>
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Reinstall the caliper on the anchor plate. Temporarily install a new support key (centered
                in the V-way) (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0401613">Figure 13</hotlnk>).
                <emph type="bold">Do not install the support spring.</emph>
                Secure the key to the caliper with the support key retaining bolt.
            </para>
            <figure id="f0401613" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0401613" filename="../figg04/G0401613.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 13. Bumper Gap Dimension (Single Piston Caliper)</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Insert a suitable pry tool (large screw- driver) between the caliper and the support key and
                pry firmly to assure that the caliper is seated against the three sliding surfaces "A" "B" "C" (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0401613">Figure 13</hotlnk>).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Measure bumper gap (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0401613">Figure 13</hotlnk>) formed between the support key and caliper using a feeler
                gauge.
                <emph type="bold">Make this measurement on one side of the prying instrument then the other.</emph>
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">If the bumper gap (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0401613">Figure 13</hotlnk>) measures more than .058 inch and less than .145 inch,
                select the proper size shim from
                <hotlnk xrefid="hl0401604">Table 1</hotlnk>.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <table id="hl0401604">
            <title>TABLE 1</title>
            <tgroup cols="2">
                <colspec colname="1" colwidth="2.75in"/>
                <colspec colname="2" colwidth="2.75in"/>
                <spanspec namest="1" nameend="2" spanname="s1t2"/>
                <thead>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry colspan="2" spanname="s1t2">
                            <para>SHIM KIT FOR MEDIUM TRUCK 2.60 AND 2.88 INCH DISC BRAKES ONLY</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry colname="1">
                            <para>MEASURED BUMPER GAP</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry colname="2">
                            <para>SHIM THICKNESS REQUIRED</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry colname="1">
                            <para>0.0" to .058"</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry colname="2">
                            <para>No Shim Required</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry colname="1">
                            <para>.059" to .101"</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry colname="2">
                            <para>.025" Shim</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry colname="1">
                            <para>.102" to .145"</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry colname="2">
                            <para>.045" Shim</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry colname="1">
                            <para>Greater than .145"</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry colname="2">
                            <para>See NOTE Below</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                </tbody>
            </tgroup>
        </table>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>If the bumper gap exceeds .145 inch, it will be necessary to replace the caliper or anchor plate
                    or both. To determine which component must be replaced, remove the caliper and replace with a new
                    caliper and re-measure gap. If the bumper gap with the new caliper is between .058 and .145 inch,
                    select the proper shim from
                    <hotlnk xrefid="hl0401604">Table 1</hotlnk>. If the bumper gap with the new caliper exceeds .145
                    inch, replace anchor plate along with the caliper.
                </para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Liberally but not excessively lubricate the sliding surfaces (V-ways), support spring and
                key (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0401611">Figure 11</hotlnk>). Use Southwest grease NLGI 1-1/2.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Position shims as illustrated (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0401611">Figure 11</hotlnk>) on opposite side from support key. Hold shim in position
                and install caliper.
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <important>
                    <para>DO NOT attempt to use more than one shim.</para>
                </important>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install NEW support key, support spring and retaining bolt (supplied in Caliper Key Kit).
                Tighten bolt to 12-18 lb-ft. (17-24 N&#8226;m).
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Vehicles with Code 04145 front disc brake caliper with a 3.38 inch single piston requires
                        oversize KEYS instead of shims. Measurements for the 3.38 inch caliper piston are listed in
                        Table 2,
                        <hotlnk xrefid="hl0401606">6.1.2.</hotlnk>.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <table id="hl0401606">
            <title>TABLE 2</title>
            <tgroup cols="2">
                <colspec colname="1" colwidth="2.75in"/>
                <colspec colname="2" colwidth="2.75in"/>
                <spanspec namest="1" nameend="2" spanname="s1t2"/>
                <thead>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry colspan="2" spanname="s1t2">
                            <para>OVERSIZE KEY KITS FOR LIGHT TRUCK 3.38 INCH DISC BRAKES ONLY</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry colname="1">
                            <para>MEASURED BUMPER GAP</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry colname="2">
                            <para>KEY SIZE</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry colname="1">
                            <para>0.0" to .060"</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry colname="2">
                            <para>Std.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry colname="1">
                            <para>.061" to .100"</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry colname="2">
                            <para>.040" O.S.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry colname="1">
                            <para>.101" to .140"</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry colname="2">
                            <para>.080" O.S.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry colname="1">
                            <para>.141" to .180"</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry colname="2">
                            <para>.120" O.S.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry colname="1">
                            <para>.181" to .220"</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry colname="2">
                            <para>.160" O.S.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry colname="1">
                            <para>Greater than .220"</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry colname="2">
                            <para>See NOTE Below</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                </tbody>
            </tgroup>
        </table>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>If the measured bumper gap exceeds the maximum shown for the shim or oversize key kit, it will be
                    necessary to replace the caliper or anchor plate, or both. To determine which component must be
                    replaced, install a new caliper in the existing anchor plate and again measure the "bumper gap." If
                    the "bumper gap" is greater than the maximum shown, replace the anchor plate and remeasure using the
                    old caliper. If the "bumper gap" is still greater than the maximum shown, install the new caliper on
                    the new anchor plate. Use
                    <hotlnk xrefid="hl0401606">Table 2</hotlnk>
                    for measurements.
                </para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
    </svcproc>
